Modular Chains

Arweave, AO, and AI - Modular Framework with Flexible Security
Seth Bloomberg

May 30, 2024 ⋅  16 min read

Key Insights

  • AO is a new protocol built on top of the permanent data storage layer, Arweave. One of AO’s core value propositions is its ability to run applications (processes in AO terminology) in parallel and maintain the associated state locally instead of requiring a shared global state.
  • All applications on AO communicate via a defined message standard, enabling an out-of-the-box solution for processes to read and write data to each other.
  • A unique property of AO is the ability to flexibly scale the security value underlying a process. Process developers can configure how much security their application requires and scale it by effectively paying for additional validators (Compute Units in AO terminology) to compute the state of the application.
  • Due to AO's scalability properties, VM-agnostic architecture, and native cron job functionality, many teams are seeking to build automation tooling and AI-powered products on the network.

Over the course of the past couple of years, two crypto infrastructure patterns have emerged: modularity and flexible security.

Modular frameworks, in contrast to integrated chains such as Solana, enable developers to select specific providers of general blockchain components (i.e., execution, data availability, settlement, and consensus) and stitch them together. Within the modularity trend, rollups, such as Base, continue to attract new users and capital. Celestia, a leading DA provider, is witnessing the classic hockey stick growth model as more rollups begin leveraging its services.

The most prominent, current example of a flexible and scalable security provider is EigenLayer. Instead of bootstrapping their own operators or validator sets, networks (e.g., rollups, coprocessors, or, more generally, offchain services) can effectively rent security from EigenLayer. With this model, EigenLayer aims to enable these networks to secure their services more efficiently than they otherwise could independently while allowing them to scale up their security in relation to the value flowing through the network.

The modular framework's goal is to encourage optionality and specialization within each component. For example, developers are free to choose which execution environment best suits their needs. Flexible security providers like EigenLayer help networks better manage and fine-tune the economic security of their systems.

One of the latest examples that taps into both of these infrastructure development patterns is AO. This new system built on Arweave gives developers the optionality of choosing their own execution environment and security model.

Instead of a single, global notion of state (e.g., user account balances, smart contract data, etc) that chains like Ethereum and Solana have, AO keeps state localized to each application (processes in AO terminology). Localized state enables applications to more easily parallelize computation, creating general performance improvements relative to non-parallelized environments, and customize the security backing the computation.

Unlike other rollup ecosystems, AO defines a global messaging standard that all applications adhere to. This approach is similar conceptually to the Cosmos ecosystem, which leverages IBC for chain-to-chain communication. AO can then maintain its modular framework, and as its ecosystem grows, applications will benefit from this native communication standard.

AO's departure from the traditional smart contract platform model leads to its own unique architecture and constructs and, over the long term, will ideally enable a thriving ecosystem of applications.

AO Architecture

The relationship between AO and Arweave loosely follows that of a sovereign rollup and a Data Availability layer. However, AO provides a general framework for developing applications (similar to smart contract platforms), and its primary goal is to enable these disparate applications to interoperate trustlessly via scalable computing services.

Interoperability between applications stems from AO’s messaging standard. Ecosystems such as Optimism, Polygon, Arbtritum, and zkSync have all generally worked towards developing chain economic activity first, and are now developing solutions interoperability solutions to solve the fractured UX issue. AO, on the other hand, will begin its journey with native interoperability.

While the AO architecture has its own jargon and unique terminology, the overall design captures all the typical blockchain components.

Processes

From an end user perspective, a process can be thought of as an application. If consumers are using a product built on AO, it will generally be represented as a process.

When building a process, developers define the below parameters along with other (not included below) lower-level specifications:

  • the scheduler (to be defined in Scheduler Units) associated with the process;
  • the underlying VM (e.g., Ethereum Virtual Machine) to be leveraged, as AO is VM-agnostic;
  • the maximum amount of memory to be used by the process.

A process can also be viewed as a series of ordered logs (i.e., messages) written to Arweave, which represent its state at any given point in time.

Each process functions independently relative to other processes on AO, enabling them to be parallelized. Processes interact with each other via messages. The concept of a message is a core construct in AO, as it is effectively a message-passing protocol.

Messages and Messenger Units

Each interaction with a process (app), whether initiated by an end user or by another process, is represented as a message. Every message in AO conforms to a specific format known as ANS-104.

Processes only interact with each other through these messages, which is a wholly different model than more traditional networks like Ethereum. For example, in AO, processes request information from another process via a message and wait for the data to be returned. Alternatively, on Ethereum, applications (i.e., smart contracts) have direct access to the state of any other application due to the global nature of the EVM.

Messenger Units relay messages throughout the various processes built on AO. To fulfill requests, a Messenger Unit interacts with both Scheduler Units (to be defined in Scheduler Units) and Compute Units (to be defined in Compute Units).

One immediate observation is that this architecture effectively defines an interoperability standard across AO processes. From a modular perspective, standardizing upfront how disparate processes interoperate is advantageous; most modular networks (e.g., Optimism’s Superchain) are still developing these standards, creating a fractured UX for end users currently.

Scheduler Units

A Scheduler Unit can be loosely analogized to a Sequencer found in many rollup systems. Since Sequencers are responsible for a host of operations in many rollups (e.g., transaction processing, transaction ordering, ZK proof generation, etc), a Scheduler Unit is more of a subset of a typical Sequencer.

Scheduler Units primarily have two functions for the process they’re associated with:

  • Ensure each message is uniquely and sequentially ordered. This is conceptually similar to nonce incrementing in other blockchain environments such as Ethereum.
  • Ensure each message is written down to Arweave. This enables processes to access each other’s data.

Every AO process will have an associated Scheduler Unit.

Compute Units

Compute Units provide the computing power to update AO processes. Messenger Units notify Compute Units that their services are required.

A marketplace is formed between Compute Units (the supply side) and users (the demand side) that need compute for some specified process. Again, this architecture diverges from traditional blockchain models. Nodes on traditional platforms such as Ethereum are required to process transactions, whereas Compute Units can selectively bid on which processes they update.

Once the computation is complete, Compute Units provide a signed attestation of the compute output back to the originating Messenger Unit.

AO Security Model

The flexibility of the AO architecture extends to its security model as well. There is no top-down, globally-defined AO security model. This runs counter to smart contract platforms such as Ethereum; every transaction, whether a simple ETH transfer or a complicated DeFi interaction, inherits (and pays for) the same security level stemming from Ethereum’s Proof-of-Stake (PoS) mechanism. In AO, each of the core components defined in the AO Architecture section above has its own notion of a security model. As detailed below, this model allows AO applications to scale (and pay for) security as a function of perceived computational value.

Staking and Slashing All The Way Down

Currently, the reference implementation (i.e., effectively a simplified testnet) on AO uses a Proof of Authority (PoA) security mechanism. While this can be used in a production environment, it seems more likely that most developers and applications will leverage a PoS mechanism (e.g., staking and slashing the AO token).

In any case, whether PoA, PoS, or something more centralized, Arweave serves as the root of trust. All processes and messages are written down to Arweave, which has its own security model.

For AO, in a PoS model, a certain value of stake can be put up against each component, and an associated slashing mechanism is also put in place.

  • Compute Units—A Compute Unit stakes value against its signed output attestation. Anyone can challenge the output of a Compute Unit, and if it is proven to be false, its stake can be slashed.
  • Messenger Units—A Messenger Unit stakes value against the messages it relays around the system. The stake can be slashed if it is found relaying and signing invalid messages. Messenger Units can initiate a slashing event against the misbehaving Compute Unit if the invalid signatures are due to misbehaving Compute Units.
  • Scheduling Units—Scheduler Units can be slashed if they fail to properly order messages or if they don’t upload the messages to Arweave. The latter slashing event is similar in design to that of Data Availability guarantees.

Ultimately, a process can, in a sense, design its own security model. While the process's code is being executed, it can, for example, decide to disregard a certain Compute Unit or Message Unit that is deemed untrustworthy.

In particular, the Compute Unit security model has a unique relationship with AO users and processes.

The security of a process can be scaled in tandem with the perceived value of the computation. For example, a small-value payment between friends does not intuitively require the same security as a multi-million dollar B2B payment.

Impact and Challenges of the AO Architecture

The AO system has many unique properties and is still early in its implementation. However, regardless of its initial implementation, three primary considerations stand out: the nascency of its ecosystem, its security model, and serving data to applications.

Arweave Impact & New Ecosystem Challenges

One of the biggest, immediate winners from an emerging AO ecosystem is Arweave. Historically, Arweave has relied on external ecosystems (e.g., social networks, NFT storage, and blockchain state storage) to drive demand. Moving forward, AO, and every process built with it, will write data down to Arweave, providing consistent, additional demand for Arweave.

The material impact from AO on Arweave is naturally a function of the scale and types of applications that build on AO. Applications to be built on AO will likely be more similar to Web2 applications from a data perspective relative to existing crypto networks or applications. Crypto applications are typically hyper-sensitive to data costs and make focused efforts toward compressing data as much as possible. AO will need to produce log data that is useful for slashing events and serving back to applications.

To get a sense of the data a massively scaled application produces, we can consider Twitter. According to some estimates, Twitter produces ~12TB of data daily, with ~400 million daily active users globally. AO applications will obviously not achieve scale close to this any time soon. However, due to the scalability properties inherent within AO, processes will not face the same data and compute constraints that traditional smart contract applications do.

From a broader ecosystem perspective, AO faces the same challenges every new network faces:

  • Developers need incentives to join the system and begin producing applications.
  • To produce applications, developers will need to ensure tooling is ported over from existing networks (i.e., EVM tooling) or create new tooling themselves.
  • Users will need to be able to access these applications, implying wallets, bridges, and general UX are, at minimum, satisfactory.

To address these and other associated challenges, $35 million in venture capital has been committed to teams building in the AO ecosystem.

While AO is still in its infancy, many teams focused on UX, DeFi, bridges, and AI are already beginning to build.

Security Model

As noted above, processes can effectively design and scale their own security models. While this inherent flexibility is enticing, it does come at a cost. Application developers now have the onus of defining how much security is “enough” for their applications; calculating this could become complex, and mishaps could result in poor UX.

Additionally, if PoS systems abound, then this implies a tremendous variety of cryptoeconomic security and slashing conditions. Ultimately, some entity must act as a watcher and report any spotted malicious activity. Who will provide incentives for this? What will a slashing event actually entail, and what is the user impact? Given the lack of empirical evidence on the impact of slashing events in a production setting, these are broadly open questions and somewhat up to the discretion of each PoS implementation.

Some form of zero-knowledge (ZK) proofs could potentially assuage these issues since ZK proofs can replace cryptoeconomic security with cryptographic guarantees. However, these ZK systems would first need to be developed, tested, optimized, and eventually implemented, which puts them in a longer-term solution category.

Data Indexing and Serving

Arweave is an established data storage protocol which will benefit the AO ecosystem. Storing data for an application is wholly different from serving data to an application, though. Even milliseconds of latency in serving data can cause user churn within an application.

So, how do applications and users access the data stored on Arweave? Primarily via gateways, such as what AR.IO provides. Gateways are complex systems, but one of their core functions is to serve up data that is written down to Arweave. Just as Arweave will benefit from a burgeoning AO ecosystem, Gateways like AR.IO will likely also see a direct positive impact.

The exact latency of an application will ultimately depend on a variety of factors, such as the performance of a gateway and the degree to which Messenger, Compute, and Scheduler units are co-located. For reference, Sam Williams, the founder of Arweave, claims round-trip (i.e., a user-initiated message resulting in some completion message back to the user) message latency is currently ~500 milliseconds. For a fast-paced gaming application, this would create a “laggy” feeling UX, but for most applications, even some consumer applications, this would likely be acceptable.

The Future of AO and AI

As noted above, teams are already building projects in various sectors within AO. One sector in particular stands out, though: AI.

However, the term “AI” can span a wide spectrum. As Mason Nystrom notes, AI or AI Agents can be purely deterministic and fully parameterized (e.g., Telegram bots with configurable settings) or, on the other side, non-deterministic with adaptive capabilities (e.g., ChatGPT or LLM applications). In AO’s case, and for almost every other smart contract platform, “AI” usage will at least begin on the purely deterministic side of the spectrum. For end-users, this will feel like using a telegram bot or, more generally, using a DeFi automation tool.

DeFi Automation

One of the early DeFi automation builders on AO is Autonomous Finance. The team has built out a “DCA Agent,” enabling users to DCA (dollar-cost average) into a specified token.

The DCA Agent product follows a general pattern:

  • Users define which token they wish to DCA into, along with other parameters such as slippage tolerance, the specific DeFi pool, the frequency of DCA transactions, and the amount they would swap in each DCA transaction.
  • The DCA Agent responds to notifications it receives (i.e., cron jobs) and executes the DCA transaction if the predefined conditions are met.
  • Users can eventually pause the DCA Agent or permanently retire it.

To be clear, the DCA Agent in this scenario does not possess “Agentic” properties; there is no LLM (e.g., ChatGPT) integrated into the workflow. It performs actions in a rule-based manner and effectively follows instructions defined in its underlying scripts. This categorically places it on the purely deterministic and parameterized end of the “AI Agent” spectrum.

This is not inherently problematic. In fact, for many users interacting with DeFi, the safest way to achieve some goal is by setting strict rules and actions for an Agent to follow. This is really pulling these products closer to parity with traditional financial products and features (e.g., setting stop losses, setting up a DCA product from your bank account, etc), which, from a UX perspective, is a good thing.

One unique AO feature that the Autonomous Finance team leverages is AO’s native cron job functionality. Cron jobs are regularly scheduled tasks or jobs that a system runs. In this case, the cron job periodically (defined by the user) reminds the DCA Agent to perform the swap if the conditions are met. These cron job frameworks are built natively into AO, whereas most other smart contract platforms rely on external third parties for these operations.

Beyond DeFi Automation

Most of the current AI excitement and hype is centered further down the Agent spectrum. These are non-deterministic Agents that can leverage LLMs and effectively decide, build, or acquire other requisite tools to complete a task. Additionally, they can react and adapt to new or novel user inputs.

These types of systems are wholly different from products like the “DCA Agent” described above. While there are a host of different challenges to consider around LLM-based agents, two primary issues are the cost structures of LLM-based products and how Agents discover or acquire new “tools” for task completion.

First and foremost, LLMs are expensive. Generally, LLM products require GPUs to provide the necessary computing power, and GPU compute is much more costly than the typical compute provided by a CPU. The cost of self-hosting an LLM foundation model can easily reach ~$20,000 per month. Additionally, according to a16z, some generative AI startups have spent 80% of their venture funding solely on AI compute. Anyone building applications on AO that leverage LLMs will naturally need to deal with their economics, there is no getting around these costs. However, AO’s architecture does enable developers to scale and fine-tune the security level of their processes. This structure will highly benefit AO developers assuming most of the messages generated from LLMs will be lower value. On other smart contract platforms, fine-tuning security costs is typically not possible.

Now, consider an AI Agent that wants to perform a token swap on behalf of a user. If the user does not give explicit instructions on which pool to use, and the Agent is not hardcoded with that information, how does it know the proper smart contracts to use to perform the swap? This can be a very complex problem, especially on open, permissionless systems like smart contract platforms. On AO, as new DeFi products emerge, AI Agents will need a mechanism to keep track of new pools and tokens and to have some ability to discern which protocols are trustworthy. However, this problem is not unique to AO; any ecosystem incorporating AI Agents will naturally face this challenge.

One solution that has emerged outside of AO is the Wayfinder protocol, which, in some sense, functions as a discoverability platform for AI Agents to leverage. Protocol developers can effectively post and stake some value against their protocols on Wayfinder, which AI Agents can then parse and use when necessary. A system like this will likely be very valuable in an emerging DeFi setting.

Final Thoughts

AO’s unique architecture provides an appealing platform for application development, ranging from DeFi to AI-powered applications.

Asynchronous messaging coupled with parallel computing enables applications to be much richer and more complex than typical smart contract applications. These applications are generally bounded by the cost of the computation and a discrete block size limit, which provides an upper bound on their overall complexity; AO processes do not have these same limitations.

The scalable and granular security backing processes are also unique to AO, and applications, especially LLM-based products, will take advantage of this property. Moving forward, these unique properties of AO will need to help propel the system past the cold-start problem every new ecosystem faces.
